My take on the classic "Visit Palestine" tourism poster. While the original was created in the 1930's to encourage zionist tourism and settlement in the holy land, it has since been repurposed by Palestinians in many ways, one being to symbolize rejection of increased popularity of Israeli tourism and instead encouraging visiting Palestine to witness the reality of the Israeli occupation first-hand. While on my trip in Palestine with @eyewitnesspalestine a few months ago, I along with my peers were constantly reminded of what a completely different experience we were getting compared to the majority of those that come on what is essentially an Israeli propaganda tour, never setting foot in the West Bank or learning a thing about the occupation. Visiting the West Bank and learning about the reality of the land we were on and the ongoing pertinent issues Palestinians face daily while also simultaneously experiencing so much richness, beauty, hospitality and joy within the culture and on the land was an invaluable experience.  I made this with that warmth and awe-struck feeling in mind. ❤️
Prints and posters of this piece are up in my shop✨

Sitti's kitchen - A 3d model of a reimagined Palestinian kitchen at golden hour 🍇 
I was inspired by Palestinian architecture & interiors, specifically by limestone & how it adds such a cozy and warm energy to a home. While in Palestine I noticed how the interiors & exteriors of homes and buildings seem to be overrun by the most beautiful plants and flowers adorning them – I wanted to capture that harmony between the inside and outside worlds, and hope to make them feel like one. 
I plan on creating many more 3d scenes of Palestine for an interactive game experience one day and am excited about using this medium to tell stories, but for now, I hope these demos are received well, and I have a ton of fun making them and learning something new. 😇

The Dome of the Rock (قبة الصخرة) – Palestine's most recognizable & iconic landmark that is /the/ oldest surviving work of Islamic Architecture (built between 688-692). It's the stunning combination of crosscultural aesthetic influences and artistic traditions, adorned with mosaics, motifs and religious inscriptions that have been recombined and reinterpreted throughout its history and multiple restoration projects. 
The draw this monument has to an artist is obvious, and after seeing it in person I was completely struck by its presence. For this illustration I wanted to focus on capturing the grandeur feeling of first seeing it and the impressions it left on me. I could get lost for many more hours studying and working on the details of the interior and exterior, and at some point I probably will – every time I tackle drawing this monument it teaches me so much.

Prints of this piece are for sale in my shop. ❤️

"Rooted"
this piece has multiple different influences conceptually so sorry if my thoughts are a bit jumbled! it started in the realm of returning home and seeing the world through your grandparents eyes, but got me to thinking about what's inherited: senses of belonging, senses of self, your will, your name, your heritage, your land, your people, the way you view the world and the way the world views you...it turned my focus onto the immense power that comes with challenging and reimagining some of what's been passed down, and how one can reorient the direction of their story while still remaining true to its origin. i'm not sure if that makes a ton of sense, but it's an idea that's stuck with me throughout my life, so I'm happy I got to somehow incorporate that feeling into a piece.

Prints of this piece are for sale in my shop. ✨

in recent weeks with all eyes on Gaza, creating to honor Palestinian culture in its many forms has offerred me a kind of personal respite.

Tatreez | تطريز
behind every intricately embroidered Palestinian thobe is a woman, honoring and passing on the knowledge and traditions of her ancestors in garments that will continue to be worn and celebrated for generations, long after they are gone. Within every hand stitched thobe is a story, a history, a community, an expression of creativity, a perseverance, and a labor of love. This piece is not only to commemorate this indigenous art form, but also the women behind it.

Just three days ago Ahed Tamimi was released in a hostage exchange after her abduction by the IOF. Ahed is one of the fiercest faces of Palestinian bravery and resistance from a young age, and has been arrested multiple times before due to being a high-profile Palestinian – this time however, her release was harrowing and markedly different from times before. Upon her release she spoke of other women still imprisoned facing inhumane conditions- being beaten, tortured, sexually assaulted, deprived of clothing, food or medication. She herself was threatened that the IOF would kill her father, who is still imprisoned, if she spoke up. The reality of wartime violence against women that Palestinian women are now suffering through as reported from eyewitness testimony is, unsurprisingly, of no note to the media. 

The violence Palestinians are facing from Israel extends beyond the genocide happening in Gaza and is all-encompassing. Within "Israeli" territory and the West Bank, Palestinians are being targeted and terrorized. Within the diaspora, we're witnessing hate crime after hate crime as anti-Palestinian and anti-arab sentiments find themselves resembling a fresh post-9/11 world. We're watching this unfold while being ultra-conscious of the spaces we occupy, how our colleagues view us, risking jobs and opportunities speaking up, figuring out how to do a dance between leveling our words to make people understand while having to censor the absolute anguish and anger that comes with that. 

To be American and to claim to care about the principles founded in recognizing the human rights of others, of feminism, of racial equality, of the right to live...and to not say anything against the human rights violations you are bearing witness to? To continue sharing community spaces, classrooms, studios, etc. with us while you silently watch us die and be abused as an observer?  You can make your own conclusions about your professed values. 

Long live Ahed Tamimi, her bravery and her spirit that persists despite the abject violence that has followed her and all Palestinians their entire lives. We are lucky that we are able to learn from them what it means to be courageous.

‎فلسطين بتعيش....وادي فوكين بتعيش | Palestine lives...Wadi Foquin Lives🇵🇸 
➡️ ➡️ SWIPE TO LEARN A BIT ABOUT THE PALESTINIAN VILLAGE OF WADI FOQUIN, a microcosm of the dangers and erasure that Israeli occupation and settlement expansion poses to Palestinians in the west bank.
inspired by my visit to Wadi Foquin with @eyewitnesspalestine last year, and a particular image of villager Yousef Manasra pointing toward illegal settlements encroaching on the small village of Wadi Foquin in Bethlehem. I was also touched by the story of solidarity told through soccer, and wanted to emphasize how meaningful these types of actions are for people living under occupation - things we otherwise take for granted.
We learned about challenges around contaminated water, farming, food supply & production, land confiscation, displacement, demolition orders, and restriction of movement that they face, all as a result of the Israeli occupation and illegal settlement expansions. 

We visited their only playground and learned about the impact of international solidarity turning into active and engaged support of their community as we learned of their partnership with a California-based organization Friends of Wadi Foquin, who supports community and economic development projects to sustain the village's survival. These projects include organizing economic development opportunities and social support for the villages women, youth education and involvement, economic survival through the cultivation of the village's honey, the establishment of a community center and soccer field, and exposure trips to the village.

Prints of this piece are available in my shop and 100% of proceeds from this print will be donated to Friends of Wadi Foquin's community project efforts. Alternatively, you can donate directly - links are in my bio. 

*information sourced from village residents, Friends of Wadi Foquin, and WRMEA article on the soccer tournament

Thobes of Palestine II - A variety of dress styles to showcase the diversity and creativity that exists within Palestinian culture. Learning about Palestinian embroidery has been a passion of mine ever since I first started illustrating our culture a couple of years ago and was completely taken aback by how unfamiliar I was with the images I was finding of dresses that were claimed as Palestinian. With time I've learned to not feel shame about that initial ignorance - our distance from our roots or our lack of knowledge about them is an intended effect of the nakba, a natural consequence of the attempt to erase our people and our connection to them, and all too common of an experience for us raised in the diaspora. The idea that our dresses are all interchangeable with other Arab cultures serves as another way to deny the existence of a distinct Palestinian identity. These dresses, their variations between cities and villages, and the stories within them continue to carry on the evidence of that identity. 

This selection doesn't necessarily represent the default style for the cities, but may reflect a variation that exists within one of its villages (such as Al Dahiriya in Al Khalil, or Beit Dajan in Yafa)
Many of these were pulled from the Widad Kawar collection. In her words in the book "Threads of Identity", "by connecting with our past, we are better able to create our future." 🕊️
